=======================================================================
               Universal Mouse Configurator v9 
                      Linux Setup Guide
=======================================================================

📋 DESCRIPTION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
This is a standalone GUI application for configuring mouse options 
(DPI, RGB lighting, Polling Rate) on various Linux distributions. 
The executable is a self-contained ELF binary and does not require 
Python or any external Python libraries to be installed on your system.


⚠️ CRITICAL STEP: UNLOCKING HARDWARE ACCESS (Udev Rules)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
By default, Linux limits regular users from directly reading or writing 
to HID interface ports (such as mice). To run this application WITHOUT 
requiring root/sudo privileges every time, we have included an intelligent 
permission script that automatically handles this for any connected mouse.

Steps to apply:
1. Open your Terminal inside the application folder.
2. Run the automated permission script using this command:
   ./setup_permissions.sh

3. The system will prompt you for your administrator (sudo) password 
   to write the rule files.
4. The script will auto-detect your mouse and immediately open up its 
   active communication port.


🚀 LAUNCHING THE APPLICATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Once permissions are successfully applied via the script above, you can 
launch the program immediately:

1. Ensure the application has execution permissions:
   chmod +x MouseConfigurator

2. Launch it via double-click or using the terminal:
   ./MouseConfigurator

💡 Note: If you are using an older environment or a Wayland-based display 
server and encounter UI launching issues, enforce the X11 compatibility layer:
   QT_QPA_PLATFORM=xcb ./MouseConfigurator


🔧 TROUBLESHOOTING & COMMON ISSUES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Issue: "Permission denied" when accessing hidraw interfaces
  Solution: Make sure you executed `./setup_permissions.sh` first. If it 
  persists, physically unplug your mouse (or wireless USB dongle) and plug 
  it back in to force the kernel to update its permission attributes.

• Issue: Missing library error regarding "libfuse.so.2"
  Solution: Your Linux distribution needs the fundamental FUSE library package:
  - Ubuntu/Debian/Mint: sudo apt install libfuse2
  - Fedora:             sudo dnf install fuse-libs
  - Arch Linux:         sudo pacman -S fuse2

• Issue: Mouse temporarily freezes upon application startup
  Solution: The application securely connects to the mouse configuration 
  sub-interfaces (Interface 2/3) and NOT the tracking sensor interface. 
  If a freeze occurs, close the app immediately and replug your mouse.
